<paper id="1924552249"><title>SATCHMO: A Theorem Prover Implemented in Prolog</title><year>1988</year><authors><author org="ECRC" id="2158063412">Rainer Manthey</author><author org="ECRC" id="870525885">Fran√ßois Bry</author></authors><n_citation>276</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>349156734</reference><reference>1511227906</reference><reference>1691379155</reference><reference>1974299393</reference><reference>2051033340</reference><reference>2058366449</reference><reference>2119295867</reference><reference>2126583599</reference></references><venue id="1134440762" type="C">Conference on Automated Deduction</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0012847</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.42643">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.57664">Horn clause</keyword><keyword weight="0.43109">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.51613">Automated theorem proving</keyword><keyword weight="0.42244">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.51894">Conjunctive normal form</keyword><keyword weight="0.54521">Prolog</keyword><keyword weight="0.46278">Differentiation rules</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Satchmo is a theorem prover consisting of just a few short and simple Prolog programs. Prolog may be used for representing problem clauses as well. SATCHMO is based on a model-generation paradigm. It is refutation-complete if used in a level-saturation manner. The paper provides a thorough report on experiences with SATCHMO. A considerable amount of problems could be solved with surprising efficiency.</abstract></paper>